We run into an issue when we look at the song table for the splash screen. The
very first note played is low [[3F]]. This is closest to [[G5]], although it
results in a frequency of [[771.9]] Hz, which is less accurate than the [[783.7]] Hz
that would be given by [[3F]]. In fact, all the low tones are off by a bit,
unless we assume that the programmer erred, thinking that the low tones were
just one octave below the high tones. In that case, we should just use the high
tone table and subtract one octave for the low tones.

<<song table>>=
SPLASH_SONG:
    LOW
    TONE 3F, 65     ; G5  @ 655ms
    HIGH
    TONE 3F, 49     ; G6  @ 469ms
    TONE 3F, 8A     ; G6  @ 887ms
    TONE 3F, 8A     ; G6  @ 887ms
    TONE 3F, 8A     ; G6  @ 887ms
    TONE 3F, 5C     ; G6  @ 591ms
    LOW
    TONE C1, 0C     ; C4  @ 231ms
    TONE 80, 04     ; G4  @  51ms
    TONE 50, 06     ; Eb5 @  49ms
    TONE 3F, 08     ; G5  @  52ms
    HIGH
    TONE 60, 0A     ; C6  @  97ms (tone inaccurate)
    TONE 50, 0C     ; Eb5 @  97ms
    TONE 3F, 2E     ; G6  @ 296ms
    TONE 47, 1B     ; F5  @ 195ms
    TONE 3F, 1F     ; G6  @ 199ms
    TONE 47, 1B     ; F5  @ 195ms
    TONE 50, 18     ; Eb5 @ 194ms
    TONE 47, 1B     ; F5  @ 195ms
    TONE 50, 18     ; Eb5 @ 194ms
    TONE 55, 17     ; D6  @ 197ms (tone inaccurate)
@

The [[start_sound]] routine goes through a sound table, executing each
instruction until it encounters a [[TONE]] instruction. It then
plays that tone, and then jumps to a routine given by [[indirect_routine]]. This
routine should do something, and then return to the song-playing loop by
jumping to [[next_table_entry]]. This allows the game to play a sound while doing
something else, for example, animating the splash screen at the beginning of the
game, and also interrupts the sound on keypress or joystick button press.

If [[start_sound]] encounters an [[END]] instruction, it returns, and that ends
the song.

[[start_sound]] also checks for a keypress or a joystick button press, and this
is the same as an [[END]] instruction.

\chapter{The Attract Screen}
\label{ch:attract}

When the main program starts at [[$0800]], it calls [[GAME_INIT]] to set up
hardware and graphics, then checks [[$5A01]]. If zero (first run), it enters
the \emph{attract screen}---the title sequence that cycles through story scenes
until the player presses a key.

\section{Top-level flow}

\subsection{Main entry (\$0800)}

The first thing the main program does:

<<main entry>>=
    ORG     $0800
MAIN_ENTRY:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     GAME_INIT
    LDA     #$09                    ; \
    STA     $FA                     ;  | $FA/$FB = $4009 (character record base)
    LDA     #$40                    ;  |
    STA     $FB                     ; /
    LDA     $5A01                   ; first-run flag
    BNE     .skip                   ; nonzero = game in progress
    JSR     ATTRACT_SCREEN
.skip:
    ; ... continues to game loop ...
@ %def MAIN_ENTRY

<<defines>>=
LOCATION_FLAG       EQU     $5A55   ; location-change flag
LOCATION_FLAG2      EQU     $5A56   ; secondary location flag
SCENE_NUMBER        EQU     $5A99   ; current scene number
ATTRACT_FLAG        EQU     $5AA7   ; 1 = attract/demo mode, 0 = normal
@ %def LOCATION_FLAG LOCATION_FLAG2 SCENE_NUMBER ATTRACT_FLAG

\subsection{game\_init (\$78C7)}

Sets up the Apple II for the game---reset vector, graphics mode, and
various subsystem initialization.

<<game init>>=
    ORG     $78C7
GAME_INIT:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDX     #$6F                    ; \
    LDY     #$A5                    ;  | reset vector = $A56F
    STX     $03F2                   ;  |
    STY     $03F3                   ; /
    JSR     $FB6F                   ; ROM: set reset vector checksum
    LDA     #$14
    STA     BLINK_COL               ; disable blink cursor
    JSR     RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING  ; copy $2000+ to $9600+/$B300+
    LDA     $C050                   ; GR mode
    LDA     $C052                   ; full screen (no text split)
    LDA     $C054                   ; page 1
    LDA     $C057                   ; hi-res
    JSR     $6C2E
    JSR     $791A
    JSR     $773A
    JSR     $7919
    JSR     $5B00
    JSR     $743B
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    JSR     $6B94
    LDA     #$00                    ; \
    STA     LOCATION_FLAG           ;  | clear state variables
    STA     LOCATION_FLAG2          ;  |
    STA     $F9                     ; /
    JSR     $084E
    JSR     $62E5
    JSR     $0C51
    LDA     #$01
    STA     $5A02                   ; current player = 1
    RTS
@ %def GAME_INIT

The soft-switch reads at [[$C050]]--[[$C057]] configure the Apple II display:
[[GR]], full-screen (no split text), page 1, hi-res. This puts the display
into HGR mode showing the framebuffer at [[$2000]]--[[$3FFF]].

\subsection{attract\_screen (\$09F4)}
\label{sec:attract_screen}

<<attract screen>>=
    ORG     $09F4
ATTRACT_SCREEN:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$01
    STA     $5A29                   ; scene/character index = 1
    STA     $423E                   ; flag
    JSR     COMPUTE_SCENE_PTR       ; scene 1 pointer → $BA/$BB
    LDA     $BA                     ; \
    STA     $F4                     ;  | $F4/$F5 = $BA/$BB (save pointer)
    LDA     $BB                     ;  |
    STA     $F5                     ; /
    JSR     SCENE_SETUP
    LDA     #$00
    STA     LOCATION_FLAG           ; clear location-change flag
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #$26                    ; scene number $26 (38 decimal)
    JMP     SCENE_LOOP              ; tail-call
@ %def ATTRACT_SCREEN

The attract screen starts with scene index 1 (the first story character
setup) and begins playing scene \$26.

\subsection{scene\_setup (\$0A17)}

Initializes a scene for display.  Loads the character record for index
[[\$5A29]], reads the character's bounding box from bytes~3--4 of the
record at [[\$BE]], converts to column/row ranges, picks a random
position within those bounds, sets the font cursor there, and performs
additional character-record bookkeeping.

The bounding box bytes are packed map positions decoded by
[[POS\_TO\_COLROW]].  The routine increments the minimums (so the range
is exclusive of the border), then calls [[RANDOM\_IN\_RANGE]] twice to
pick a random column and row within the bounds.

<<scene setup>>=
    ORG     $0A17
SCENE_SETUP:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     $5A29                   ; character/scene index
    JSR     $1053                   ; load character record → $BE
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     ($BE),Y                 ; byte 3: min position (packed)
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW           ; → A=min_col, Y=min_row
    STA     $5A51                   ; min_col
    STY     $5A53                   ; min_row
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     ($BE),Y                 ; byte 4: max position (packed)
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW           ; → A=max_col, Y=max_row
    STA     $5A52                   ; max_col
    STY     $5A54                   ; max_row
    INC     $5A51                   ; min_col++ (exclusive border)
    INC     $5A53                   ; min_row++
    CLC
    LDA     $5A52                   ; \
    SBC     $5A51                   ;  | col_range = max_col - min_col
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE         ;  | random column offset
    CLC                             ;  |
    ADC     $5A51                   ;  | col = min_col + offset
    STA     FONT_COL                ; / set font column
    CLC
    LDA     $5A54                   ; \
    SBC     $5A53                   ;  | row_range = max_row - min_row
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE         ;  | random row offset
    CLC                             ;  |
    ADC     $5A53                   ; / row = min_row + offset
    TAY                             ; Y = row
    LDA     FONT_COL                ; A = col
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS           ; → A = linear position
    LDY     #$03
    STA     ($F4),Y                 ; store position in record byte 3
    LDA     $F4                     ; \
    STA     $BC                     ;  | $BC/$BD = $F4/$F5
    LDA     $F5                     ;  |
    STA     $BD                     ; /
    LDA     #$00
    STA     $5A28                   ; clear player index
    JSR     $0F84                   ; character record management
    LDY     #$0D
    LDA     #$00                    ; \
    STA     ($F4),Y                 ;  | clear bytes 13-14 of record
    INY                             ;  |
    STA     ($F4),Y                 ; /
    JSR     CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD        ; ensure byte 6 >= byte 5 minimum
    LDA     $5A02                   ; current player index
    CMP     $5A29                   ; compare with scene index
    BNE     .done                   ; not current player → skip
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     ($F4),Y                 ; load position from record
    JSR     DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS        ; draw character at position
.done:
    RTS
@ %def SCENE_SETUP

\subsection{scene\_loop (\$6C37)}
\label{sec:scene_loop}

This is the main scene display loop.  It is called with the scene number
in~A.

<<scene loop>>=
    ORG     $6C37
SCENE_LOOP:
    SUBROUTINE

    STA     SCENE_NUMBER            ; store scene number
    LDA     #$14
    STA     BLINK_COL               ; disable blink cursor

    JSR     SAVE_ZP_POINTERS

    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT             ; PRNG output
    AND     #$0A                    ; test bits 1 and 3
    BNE     .display                ; if any set, skip disk load
    JSR     LOAD_SCENE_DATA

.display:
    JSR     $A478                   ; keyboard/timing check (EALDR resident)
    BCS     .exit                   ; carry set = user pressed key

    JSR     DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR
    LDA     #<$5C00                 ; \
    STA     $06                     ;  | $06/$07 = $5C00 (scene text data)
    LDA     #>$5C00                 ;  |
    STA     $07                     ; /
    JSR     TEXT_RENDERER

    LDX     #$06                    ; script index 6
    JSR     SCRIPT_ENGINE           ; run script #3 ($A300)
    LDA     $5CFF                   ; scene transition flag
    BEQ     .done                   ; zero = no transition
    STA     SCENE_NUMBER            ; set new scene number
    JMP     .display                ; continue

.exit:
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    LDA     #$1B
    JSR     $761E                   ; sound/mode off
                                    ; fall through to .done

.done:
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    LDA     #$00                    ; \
    STA     LOCATION_FLAG           ;  | clear location flags
    STA     LOCATION_FLAG2          ; /
    JSR     $72A7                   ; update display
    JMP     RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS     ; restore and return
@ %def SCENE_LOOP

The scene loop calls [[$A478]] (a resident routine from EALDR, still in
memory at [[$A000]]--[[$BFFF]]) each iteration to check for user input.
If carry is set (key pressed), the loop exits.  Otherwise, it displays
the status bar, renders the scene text from [[$5C00]], runs script \#3
(the attract animation at [[$A300]]), and checks [[$5CFF]] for a scene
transition.

The [[$5C00]] region is populated dynamically by [[LOAD\_SCENE\_DATA]]
from disk.  Its contents change with each scene.

\section{Utility routines}

\subsection{save\_zp\_pointers / restore\_zp\_pointers}

These routines save and restore four zero-page pointer pairs to/from
fixed addresses in the [[$5A00]] page.  The pointers are used throughout
the game for character records, text buffers, and cursor state.

<<defines>>=
SAVED_BC            EQU     $5A9A   ; saved $BC/$BD pointer (2 bytes)
SAVED_F8            EQU     $5A9C   ; saved $F8/$F9 pointer (2 bytes)
SAVED_BE            EQU     $5A9E   ; saved $BE/$BF pointer (2 bytes)
SAVED_F4            EQU     $5AA0   ; saved $F4/$F5 pointer (2 bytes)
@ %def SAVED_BC SAVED_F8 SAVED_BE SAVED_F4

<<save zp pointers>>=
    ORG     $6D53
SAVE_ZP_POINTERS:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     $BC
    STA     SAVED_BC
    LDA     $BD
    STA     SAVED_BC+1
    LDA     $F8
    STA     SAVED_F8
    LDA     $F9
    STA     SAVED_F8+1
    LDA     $BE
    STA     SAVED_BE
    LDA     $BF
    STA     SAVED_BE+1
    LDA     $F4
    STA     SAVED_F4
    LDA     $F5
    STA     SAVED_F4+1
    RTS
@ %def SAVE_ZP_POINTERS
@

<<restore zp pointers>>=
    ORG     $6D7C
RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     SAVED_BC
    STA     $BC
    LDA     SAVED_BC+1
    STA     $BD
    LDA     SAVED_F8
    STA     $F8
    LDA     SAVED_F8+1
    STA     $F9
    LDA     SAVED_BE
    STA     $BE
    LDA     SAVED_BE+1
    STA     $BF
    LDA     SAVED_F4
    STA     $F4
    LDA     SAVED_F4+1
    STA     $F5
    RTS
@ %def RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS

\subsection{relocate\_hires\_staging (\$6DA5)}

During startup, tracks [[\$0F]] and [[\$10]] are loaded into the hi-res
page area [[$2000--$3FFF]] as a staging area.  This routine, called from
[[game\_init]], copies the staged data to its runtime addresses and clears
the hi-res page:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccl}
\toprule
\thead{Source} & \thead{Destination} & \thead{Size} \\
\midrule
\$2000--\$32FF & \$9600--\$A8FF & 19 pages (HRCG code + standard font) \\
\$3300--\$3FFF & \$B300--\$BFFF & 13 pages (disk I/O routines) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The copy loop at [[.copy]] also clears each source byte, leaving the
hi-res page zeroed for use as a graphics buffer.

<<relocate hires staging>>=
    ORG     $6DA5
RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$00
    STA     $BA                         ; \  dest = $9600
    STA     $BC                         ; \  src  = $2000
    LDA     #$20                        ;  |
    STA     $BD                         ; /  src hi
    LDA     #$96                        ;  |
    STA     $BB                         ; /  dest hi
    LDY     #$00
    LDX     #$13                        ; 19 pages: $2000-$32FF -> $9600-$A8FF
    JSR     .copy
    LDX     #$0D                        ; 13 pages: $3300-$3FFF -> $B300-$BFFF
    LDA     #$B3
    STA     $BB                         ; dest hi = $B3
    INC     $BD                         ; src hi = $33 (was $32 after first pass)

.copy:
    LDA     ($BC),Y                     ; load from source
    STA     ($BA),Y                     ; store to dest
    LDA     #$00
    STA     ($BC),Y                     ; clear source byte
    DEY
    BNE     .copy                       ; inner loop (256 bytes)
    DEX
    BNE     .next_page                  ; more pages?
    RTS

.next_page:
    INC     $BD                         ; next source page
    INC     $BB                         ; next dest page
    JMP     .copy
@ %def RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING

\subsection{step\_prng (\$78A8)}

The pseudo-random number generator computes:
$$\texttt{val}_{n+1} = 69 \cdot \texttt{val}_n + \$53 \pmod{256}$$
and stores both the full result and a shifted copy.

<<step prng>>=
    ORG     $78A8
STEP_PRNG:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     PRNG_STATE              ; val
    ASL     A                       ; val*2
    ASL     A                       ; val*4
    STA     PRNG_TEMP               ; temp = val*4
    ASL     A                       ; val*8
    ASL     A                       ; val*16
    ASL     A                       ; val*32
    ASL     A                       ; val*64
    CLC
    ADC     PRNG_TEMP               ; val*64 + val*4 = val*68
    CLC
    ADC     PRNG_STATE              ; val*68 + val = val*69
    CLC
    ADC     #$53                    ; + $53
    STA     PRNG_STATE              ; store full result
    LSR                             ; val >> 1
    STA     PRNG_OUTPUT             ; shifted copy (used for random tests)
    RTS
@ %def STEP_PRNG

Two shifts produce [[val*4]], saved to [[PRNG\_TEMP]].  Four more shifts give
[[val*64]].  Adding [[val*4]] gives [[val*68]], then adding [[val]] gives
[[val*69]].  Adding [[\$53]] completes the LCG step.  This is a linear
congruential generator with multiplier 69, increment \$53, and modulus 256.

\subsection{random\_in\_range (\$1317)}

Returns a uniform random integer in [[0..A$-$1]] using rejection sampling.
The routine finds the smallest bitmask that covers the range, then repeatedly
calls [[STEP\_PRNG]] and masks [[PRNG\_OUTPUT]] until the result is less than
or equal to the shifted limit.  This avoids modulo bias.

Input: A~=~range limit (1--127).  If A~=~0, returns~0 immediately.
Output: A~=~random value in [[0..limit$-$1]].

<<defines>>=
RNG_LIMIT           EQU     $5A11   ; random\_in\_range temporary (limit/shift count)
RNG_MASK            EQU     $5A12   ; random\_in\_range bit mask
@ %def RNG_LIMIT RNG_MASK

<<random in range>>=
    ORG     $1317
RANDOM_IN_RANGE:
    SUBROUTINE

    STA     RNG_LIMIT               ; save range limit
    CMP     #$00
    BNE     .nonzero
    RTS                             ; range=0 → return 0

.nonzero:
    CMP     #$02                    ; \
    BPL     .ge2                    ;  |
    LDY     #$06                    ;  | range 1: mask=$40, shift=6
    LDA     #$40                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge2:
    CMP     #$04                    ; \
    BPL     .ge4                    ;  |
    LDY     #$05                    ;  | range 2-3: mask=$60, shift=5
    LDA     #$60                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge4:
    CMP     #$08                    ; \
    BPL     .ge8                    ;  |
    LDY     #$04                    ;  | range 4-7: mask=$70, shift=4
    LDA     #$70                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge8:
    CMP     #$10                    ; \
    BPL     .ge16                   ;  |
    LDY     #$03                    ;  | range 8-15: mask=$78, shift=3
    LDA     #$78                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge16:
    CMP     #$20                    ; \
    BPL     .ge32                   ;  |
    LDY     #$02                    ;  | range 16-31: mask=$7C, shift=2
    LDA     #$7C                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge32:
    CMP     #$40                    ; \
    BPL     .ge64                   ;  |
    LDY     #$01                    ;  | range 32-63: mask=$7E, shift=1
    LDA     #$7E                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge64:
    LDY     #$00                    ; range 64-127: mask=$7F, shift=0
    LDA     #$7F

.have_mask:
    STA     RNG_MASK                ; save bit mask
    LDA     RNG_LIMIT               ; reload range limit
    STY     RNG_LIMIT               ; save shift count in RNG_LIMIT
.shift_loop:
    DEY                             ; \
    BMI     .shifted                ;  | shift limit left by (shift count)
    CLC                             ;  | positions so it aligns with the
    ROL     A                       ;  | mask bits
    BNE     .shift_loop             ; /
.shifted:
    LDY     RNG_LIMIT               ; Y = shift count
    STA     RNG_LIMIT               ; save shifted limit

.sample:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG               ; get next random byte
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    AND     RNG_MASK                ; mask to relevant bits
    CMP     RNG_LIMIT               ; compare with shifted limit
    BEQ     .accept                 ; equal → accept
    BPL     .sample                 ; greater → reject, retry

.accept:
    DEY                             ; \
    BPL     .shift_right            ;  | shift result right by (shift count)
    RTS                             ;  | to recover the final value
.shift_right:
    CLC                             ;  |
    ROR     A                       ;  |
    BCC     .accept                 ; / (always taken: masked bit is 0)
@ %def RANDOM_IN_RANGE

\subsection{clamp\_char\_field (\$0A93)}

Ensures that byte~6 of the character record at [[$F4]] has its lower 6~bits
at least as large as byte~5's lower 5~bits.  If byte~6 is smaller, its low
bits are replaced with byte~5's value (preserving byte~6's top 2~bits).
This clamps a stat floor---likely ensuring current HP does not fall below
a minimum derived from another field.

<<clamp char field>>=
    ORG     $0A93
CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$05
    LDA     ($F4),Y                 ; byte 5 of record
    AND     #$1F                    ; low 5 bits = minimum
    STA     $BA
    INY
    LDA     ($F4),Y                 ; byte 6 of record
    AND     #$3F                    ; low 6 bits = current value
    CMP     $BA
    BCC     .clamp                  ; current < minimum → clamp
    RTS                             ; current >= minimum → done
.clamp:
    LDA     ($F4),Y                 ; reload byte 6
    AND     #$C0                    ; preserve top 2 bits
    ORA     $BA                     ; set low bits to minimum
    STA     ($F4),Y
    RTS
@ %def CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD

\subsection{draw\_char\_at\_pos (\$1156)}

Given a map position in~A, sets the font cursor to the corresponding
column and row, looks up what character or mob occupies that position,
determines its font character, and draws it.

<<draw char at pos>>=
    ORG     $1156
DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW           ; A=pos → A=col, Y=row
    STA     FONT_COL                ; set font column
    STY     FONT_ROW                ; set font row
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS           ; re-linearize (A = col + row*20)
    JSR     $0B62                   ; look up entity at position → $BE
    JSR     $0C7E                   ; determine font char from entity data
    JMP     $7489                   ; render the font character
@ %def DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS

\subsection{display\_status\_bar (\$6D1F)}

Draws the ``PRESS SPACE BAR TO CONTINUE'' (or ``PRESS THE BUTTON TO
CONTINUE'') message in the text window at the bottom of the screen.

<<display status bar>>=
    ORG     $6D1F
DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$90                    ; ctrl-P with high bit (toggle inverse)
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    STOW    STATUS_BORDER_DATA,$06  ; $06/$07 → status bar border data
    JSR     TEXT_RENDERER           ; draw border box
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB           ; Ctrl-A, '0'
    LDA     #$17
    STA     TEXT_ROW                ; WNDBTM = 23

    LDA     $5A00                   ; joystick/keyboard flag
    BNE     .joystick

    ; Keyboard path:
    STOW    S_PRESS_SPACE,$BC       ; $BC/$BD → "PRESS SPACE BAR..."
.set_margin:
    LDA     #$04
    STA     TEXT_COL                ; WNDLFT = 4
    JMP     PRINT_FROM_PTR         ; print string, return

.joystick:
    STOW    S_PRESS_BUTTON,$BC      ; $BC/$BD → "PRESS THE BUTTON..."
    JMP     .set_margin
@ %def DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR

The border box data at [[STATUS\_BORDER\_DATA]] is drawn via the hi-res
text renderer.  The prompt text is printed via [[PRINT\_FROM\_PTR]].

\subsection{print\_from\_ptr (\$775C)}

Prints a length-prefixed string from [[$BC/$BD]] via COUT:

<<print from ptr>>=
    ORG     $775C
PRINT_FROM_PTR:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$00
    LDA     ($BC),Y                 ; first byte = length
    TAX
.loop:
    DEX
    BPL     .next
    RTS                             ; done

.next:
    INY
    LDA     ($BC),Y                 ; read next char
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    JMP     .loop
@ %def PRINT_FROM_PTR

\subsection{display\_message (\$761E)}

Displays a message from the game's message table.  Takes the message
index in~A.  The message table base address is stored at
[[\$4005/\$4006]]; each entry is a length-prefixed string.  The routine
walks the table to find the Xth entry, then displays up to three lines
in the status window.

For the first line ([[MSG\_LINE\_COUNT]]~=~0), it calls
[[PRINT\_BOTTOM\_CENTERED]] then scrolls.  For the second line
([[MSG\_LINE\_COUNT]]~=~1), it scrolls first, then prints.  For the
third and subsequent lines, it scrolls, prints, then calls [[\$0D10]]
(delay) and [[\$774E]] ([[PRINT\_CTRL\_AB]]) before looping back.

An entry with a zero length byte terminates the message.  If exactly
two lines were printed, a final scroll is performed on exit.

<<defines>>=
MSG_TABLE_PTR           EQU     $4005   ; message table base (2 bytes)
MSG_LINE_COUNT          EQU     $5A57   ; lines printed so far
@ %def MSG_TABLE_PTR MSG_LINE_COUNT

<<display message>>=
    ORG     $761E
DISPLAY_MESSAGE:
    SUBROUTINE

    TAX                             ; X = message index
    LDA     MSG_TABLE_PTR           ; load table base into $BC/$BD
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     MSG_TABLE_PTR+1
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    LDA     #$00
    STA     MSG_LINE_COUNT          ; reset line counter

    JMP     .check_index            ; skip to index check

.skip_entry:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y   ; get string length
    TAY
    SEC                             ; +1 for length byte itself
    ADC     PRINT_STRING_ADDR       ; advance pointer past this entry
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    ADC     #$00
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    CPY     #$00                    ; was length zero? (end of table)
    BNE     .skip_entry             ; no — keep skipping within group
.next_index:
    DEX
.check_index:
    CPX     #$00
    BNE     .skip_entry             ; more entries to skip

.print_loop:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y   ; get length of current string
    BNE     .has_text               ; nonzero — print it

    ; length is zero — message is done
    LDA     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    CMP     #$02                    ; printed exactly 2 lines?
    BEQ     .final_scroll
    RTS                             ; otherwise just return
.final_scroll:
    JMP     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE                   ; scroll once more and return

.has_text:
    LDA     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    CMP     #$01
    BMI     .first_line             ; line_count < 1: first line
    BEQ     .second_line            ; line_count == 1: second line

    ; third+ line: scroll, then print
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE                   ; scroll status window
.second_line:
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED   ; print centered on row 23
    JMP     .advance

.first_line:
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED   ; print centered on row 23
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE                   ; scroll status window

.advance:
    INC     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    SEC
    ADC     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y   ; add length + 1 (SEC sets carry)
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    ADC     #$00
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    LDA     #$01
    CMP     MSG_LINE_COUNT          ; printed <= 1 lines?
    BCC     .pause                  ; no — need to pause
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y   ; peek at next entry
    BNE     .print_loop             ; more text — keep printing

.pause:
    JSR     DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION    ; delay
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB           ; reset character set
    JMP     .print_loop             ; continue with next line
@ %def DISPLAY_MESSAGE

\subsection{print\_ctrl\_AB (\$774E)}

Sends Ctrl-A and [['0']] to COUT (selects character set~0 in the HRCG):

<<print ctrl ab>>=
    ORG     $774E
PRINT_CTRL_AB:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$81                    ; Ctrl-A with high bit
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    LDA     #$B0                    ; '0' with high bit
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@ %def PRINT_CTRL_AB

\subsection{set\_cursor\_row21 / set\_text\_window\_bottom}
\label{sec:set_text_window}

These two routines share the same code; they differ only in the
window-bottom value loaded in~A.  The BNE at [[$76C0]] forms a
``stretchy branch'' that skips the [[LDA \#\$14]], so both entry points
share all code from [[$76C4]] onward.

<<set text window bottom>>=
    ORG     $76BE
SET_CURSOR_ROW21:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$15                    ; WNDBTM = 21
    BNE     .shared                 ; always taken (stretchy branch)

SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM:
    LDA     #$14                    ; WNDBTM = 20

.shared:
    STA     TEXT_ROW
    LDA     #$00
    STA     TEXT_COL                ; WNDLFT = 0
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB
    LDA     #$86                    ; Ctrl-F with high bit
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@ %def SET_CURSOR_ROW21 SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM

\subsection{scroll\_status\_line (\SCROLL_STATUS_LINE)}

Scrolls the status window (rows 21--23) up by one line.  Sets scroll
mode, defines the text window as the status area (upper-left at
row~21), positions the cursor at row~23, outputs [[Ctrl-C]] to scroll
up, resets the window to full screen, and restores wrap mode.

<<scroll status line>>=
    ORG     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
SCROLL_STATUS_LINE:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_SCROLL   ; enable scroll mode
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_LOW ; window top = row 21
    LDA     #$17
    STA     TEXT_ROW                 ; cursor to row 23
    LDA     #$83                    ; Ctrl-C with high bit (scroll up)
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_ALL ; reset window to (0,0)
    JMP     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_WRAP     ; restore wrap mode and return
@ %def SCROLL_STATUS_LINE

\subsection{pos\_to\_colrow (\$0C25)}

Converts a packed map position (0--199) into separate column and row
values by dividing by~20.  The map is 20~columns wide, so
[[column = pos mod 20]] and [[row = pos / 20]].

The loop repeatedly subtracts~20 (via [[ADC \#\$EC]] with carry clear,
since [[\$EC = 256 $-$ 20]]), counting iterations in~[[Y]].  When the
subtraction underflows (carry clear on exit), it adds~20 back to recover
the remainder.

<<pos to colrow>>=
    ORG     $0C25
POS_TO_COLROW:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY      #$00              ; row = 0
.loop:
    CLC
    ADC      #$EC              ; A -= 20 (unsigned)
    BCC      .done             ; underflow → remainder is negative
    INY                        ; row++
    BCS      .loop             ; always taken (carry set)
.done:
    ADC      #$14              ; add 20 back → A = column (remainder)
    RTS                        ; A = column (0-19), Y = row (0-9)
@ %def POS_TO_COLROW

\subsection{colrow\_to\_pos (\$0D98)}

The inverse of [[POS\_TO\_COLROW]]: converts a column in~A and row in~Y
to a linear map position [[A = col + row * 20]].  The carry is cleared
once on entry; thereafter the loop adds~20 per row and exits early if
carry occurs (overflow past 255).

<<colrow to pos>>=
    ORG     $0D98
COLROW_TO_POS:
    SUBROUTINE

    CLC
.loop:
    DEY                         ; row--
    BPL     .add                ; still >= 0 → add another 20
    RTS                         ; Y exhausted, A = result
.add:
    ADC     #$14                ; A += 20
    BCC     .loop               ; no overflow → continue
                                ; carry set → return (overflow)
@ %def COLROW_TO_POS

\subsection{compute\_scene\_ptr (\$0C32)}

Computes a pointer into the game data from a 1-based scene index in~A.
Each scene record is 16 bytes.  The result
[[$BA/$BB = ($4000) + (index - 1) \times 16$]] is stored in [[$BA]]/[[$BB]],
where [[$4000/$4001]] holds the base address of the scene table.

<<compute scene ptr>>=
    ORG     $0C32
COMPUTE_SCENE_PTR:
    SUBROUTINE

    CLC
    ADC     #$FF                    ; A = index - 1
    ROL     A                       ; \
    ROL     A                       ;  | rotate left 4 times
    ROL     A                       ;  | = multiply by 16 (with carry)
    ROL     A                       ; /
    TAY                             ; save intermediate
    ROL     A                       ; one more rotate
    AND     #$0F                    ; high nybble → page offset
    CLC
    ADC     $4001                   ; add base page
    STA     $BB                     ; high byte
    TYA
    AND     #$F0                    ; low nybble → byte offset
    CLC
    ADC     $4000                   ; add base offset
    STA     $BA                     ; low byte
    BCC     .done
    INC     $BB                     ; carry
.done:
    RTS
@ %def COMPUTE_SCENE_PTR

\subsection{appearance\_to\_fontchar (\$0CF7)}

Converts a mob appearance index (byte~4 of mob data) into a font
character number.  The custom font has 120 characters in groups of~32,
but only 21~mob glyphs occupy each group (characters 1--21 and 33--36).
Characters 5--21 repeat cyclically for higher appearance values.

The routine divides the appearance value by~21 (via repeated subtraction
of~21), producing a quotient in~[[Y]] and a 1-based remainder in~[[A]].
If the remainder is~$\ge5$, it is returned directly.  If~$<5$ and the
quotient is nonzero, 32 is added to index into the next font group.

<<appearance to fontchar>>=
    ORG     $0CF7
APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY      #$00              ; Y = quotient (font group)
.loop:
    CLC
    ADC      #$EB              ; A -= 21 (unsigned: $EB = 256-21)
    BCC      .done             ; underflow → done dividing
    INY                        ; group++
    BCS      .loop             ; always taken
.done:
    ADC      #$16              ; restore remainder+1 (carry clear, so +22)
    CMP      #$05              ; remainder >= 5?
    BCC      .low              ; no → check group
    RTS                        ; yes → return as-is (chars 5-21)
.low:
    CPY      #$00              ; first group?
    BEQ      .ret              ; yes → return as-is (chars 1-4)
    CLC
    ADC      #$20              ; add 32 → next font group (chars 33-36)
.ret:
    RTS
@ %def APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR

\subsection{delay\_with\_animation (\$0D10)}

Delays for a configurable duration while keeping the status window
animation running.  Loads an iteration count from [[\$7ABF]] and calls
[[\$0D30]] (the per-tick animation/wait handler) that many times.
Each call to [[\$0D30]] ticks an animation counter, runs a timed wait
via the ROM [[WAIT]] routine, and advances the animation frame when
the counter expires.

<<defines>>=
DELAY_COUNT             EQU     $7ABF   ; number of delay iterations
@ %def DELAY_COUNT

<<delay with animation>>=
    ORG     $0D10
DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     DELAY_COUNT             ; load iteration count
.loop:
    PHA                             ; save counter
    JSR     ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT      ; tick animation + timed wait
    PLA                             ; restore counter
    TAY
    DEY                             ; decrement
    TYA
    BNE     .loop                   ; loop until zero
    RTS
@ %def DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION

\subsection{tick\_anim\_counter (\$0D1E)}

Decrements the animation frame counter at [[\$7AAF]].  When it reaches
zero, calls [[\$74CB]] to advance the animation frame.  Then reloads
the wait loop count from the timing table at [[\$7AB0]] (indexed by
the current animation index at [[\$7ABD]]) into [[\$5A8C]].

<<defines>>=
ANIM_FRAME_CTR          EQU     $7AAF   ; animation frame countdown
ANIM_INDEX              EQU     $7ABD   ; current animation table index
ANIM_WAIT_TABLE         EQU     $7AB0   ; per-frame wait counts (indexed)
ANIM_FRAME_TABLE        EQU     $7AB6   ; per-frame frame counts (indexed)
WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         EQU     $5A8C   ; inner wait loop counter
WAIT_DURATION           EQU     $7AAD   ; ROM WAIT duration parameter
@ %def ANIM_FRAME_CTR ANIM_INDEX ANIM_WAIT_TABLE ANIM_FRAME_TABLE WAIT_LOOP_COUNT WAIT_DURATION

<<tick anim counter>>=
    ORG     $0D1E
TICK_ANIM_COUNTER:
    SUBROUTINE

    DEC     ANIM_FRAME_CTR          ; tick frame counter
    BNE     .reload                 ; not zero → just reload wait count
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_ALT          ; counter hit zero → draw alt char
.reload:
    LDX     ANIM_INDEX              ; current animation index
    LDA     ANIM_WAIT_TABLE,X       ; look up wait count for this frame
    STA     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         ; store for timed_wait to use
    RTS
@ %def TICK_ANIM_COUNTER

\subsection{anim\_tick\_and\_wait (\$0D30)}

Combined animation tick and wait.  Calls [[TICK\_ANIM\_COUNTER]] to
decrement the frame counter and set up the wait count, then calls
[[TIMED\_WAIT]] to burn time.  If the frame counter has reached zero
(meaning the animation frame expired), calls [[\$74DD]] to update the
display and reloads the frame counter from the frame table at
[[\$7AB6]].

<<anim tick and wait>>=
    ORG     $0D30
ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     TICK_ANIM_COUNTER       ; tick counter, reload wait count
    JSR     TIMED_WAIT              ; burn time
    LDA     ANIM_FRAME_CTR          ; did frame counter expire?
    BEQ     .advance                ; yes → advance animation
    RTS                             ; no → return

.advance:
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_NORMAL       ; redraw blink char in normal video
    LDX     ANIM_INDEX              ; reload animation index
    LDA     ANIM_FRAME_TABLE,X      ; look up frame duration
    STA     ANIM_FRAME_CTR          ; reset frame counter
    RTS
@ %def ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT

\subsection{timed\_wait (\$0D49)}

Calls the ROM [[WAIT]] wrapper [[\$0D58]] repeatedly, decrementing
[[WAIT\_LOOP\_COUNT]] until it reaches zero.  If the count is already
zero on entry, returns immediately.

<<timed wait>>=
    ORG     $0D49
TIMED_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         ; anything to wait for?
    BNE     .wait                   ; yes → enter wait loop
    RTS                             ; no → return immediately

.wait:
    JSR     CALL_ROM_WAIT           ; delay one unit
    DEC     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         ; decrement counter
    BNE     .wait                   ; loop until zero
    RTS
@ %def TIMED_WAIT

\subsection{call\_rom\_wait (\$0D58)}

Loads the wait duration from [[WAIT\_DURATION]] and jumps to the
Apple~II ROM [[WAIT]] routine at [[\$FCA8]], which delays for
approximately $A \times 2.5 + 13.5$ microseconds.

<<defines>>=
ROM_WAIT                EQU     $FCA8   ; Apple II ROM WAIT routine
@ %def ROM_WAIT

<<call rom wait>>=
    ORG     $0D58
CALL_ROM_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     WAIT_DURATION           ; load duration parameter
    JMP     ROM_WAIT                ; tail-call ROM WAIT
@ %def CALL_ROM_WAIT

\section{Text renderer}
\label{sec:text_renderer}

Reads a byte stream from the pointer at [[$06/$07]] and renders
characters on the hi-res screen.  It maintains column/row state and
supports several control codes.

<<defines>>=
TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN        EQU     $5A96   ; right margin column for text wrap
TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN         EQU     $5A97   ; left margin column for text wrap
TEXT_STREAM_IDX          EQU     TEXT_STREAM_IDX   ; saved Y index into byte stream
@ %def TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN TEXT_STREAM_IDX

<<text renderer>>=
    ORG     $6C8E
TEXT_RENDERER:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$00
.init:
    LDA     #$02
    STA     TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN         ; left margin = 2
    STA     FONT_COL                ; current column = 2
    LDA     #$12
    STA     TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN       ; right margin = $12 (18)
    LDA     #$01
    STA     FONT_ROW                ; current row = 1

    ; --- Main byte-reading loop ---
.fetch:
    LDA     ($06),Y                 ; read byte from stream
    BMI     .set_pos                ; bit 7 set → position command
    CMP     #$7F
    BNE     .not_end
    RTS                             ; $7F = end of stream

.not_end:
    CMP     #$7E
    BEQ     .pause                  ; $7E = pause
    CMP     #$7D
    BEQ     .reset                  ; $7D = reset to full-screen mode

    ; --- Character output ---
    STY     TEXT_STREAM_IDX                   ; save stream index
    STA     FONT_CHARNUM            ; character code
    LDA     #$02
    STA     FONT_CHARSET            ; character width = 2
    JSR     PRINT_FONTCHAR          ; draw at current position
    INC     FONT_COL                ; advance column
    LDA     FONT_COL
    CMP     TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN       ; past right margin?
    BCC     .next                   ; no → continue
    INC     FONT_ROW                ; yes → next row
    LDA     TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN        ;   reset column to left margin
    STA     FONT_COL
.next:
    LDY     TEXT_STREAM_IDX                   ; restore stream index
    INY                             ; advance to next byte
    BNE     .fetch                  ; loop (max 256 per page)
    JMP     $1A31                   ; overflow handler

    ; --- Position command ($80-$FE) ---
.set_pos:
    AND     #$7F                    ; row = byte & $7F
    STA     FONT_ROW
    INY
    LDA     ($06),Y                 ; next byte = column
    STA     FONT_COL
    INY
    JMP     .fetch

    ; --- Pause ($7E): run script engine, show status bar ---
.pause:
    TYA                             ; \
    PHA                             ;  | save stream index
    NOP
    LDX     #$06
    JSR     SCRIPT_ENGINE           ; run attract script
    LDA     $06                     ; \
    PHA                             ;  | save $06/$07 (stream pointer)
    LDA     $07                     ;  |
    PHA                             ; /
    JSR     DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR      ; (clobbers $06/$07)
    PLA                             ; \
    STA     $07                     ;  | restore $06/$07
    PLA                             ;  |
    STA     $06                     ; /
    PLA                             ; restore stream index
    TAY
    NOP
    INY                             ; advance past $7E
    JMP     .init                   ; reinit margins/position

    ; --- Reset ($7D): full-screen text mode ---
.reset:
    LDA     #$00
    STA     TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN         ; left margin = 0
    STA     FONT_COL                ; column = 0
    STA     FONT_ROW                ; row = 0
    LDA     #$14
    STA     TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN       ; right margin = $14 (20)
    INY                             ; advance past $7D
    JMP     .fetch
@ %def TEXT_RENDERER
@

\subsection{Control code summary}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cl}
\toprule
\thead{Byte} & \thead{Meaning} \\
\midrule
\$7D & Reset to full-screen mode (col=0, row=0, width=20) \\
\$7E & Pause: run script engine and status bar, then resume \\
\$7F & End of stream \\
\$80--\$FE & Set row (byte \& \$7F), next byte = column \\
Other & Character code for HRCG font \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsection{Border data at \$7E2F}

The text renderer data at [[STATUS\_BORDER\_DATA]] draws a decorative
