@ %def STATUS_BORDER_DATA

\subsection{Status bar text strings}

<<status bar strings>>=
    ORG     $7E97
S_PRESS_SPACE:
    APSTR   "  PRESS SPACE BAR TO CONTINUE   "

S_PRESS_BUTTON:
    APSTR   "  PRESS THE BUTTON TO CONTINUE  "
@ %def S_PRESS_SPACE S_PRESS_BUTTON

\section{Resident bytecode interpreter (\$0500--\$07FF)}
\label{sec:resident_interp}

EALDR copies 768 bytes from [[$A300]]--[[$A5FF]] to [[$0500]]--[[$07FF]]
before entering the main program.  This region contains a second bytecode
interpreter, separate from the EALDR VM, that runs during gameplay and
the attract screen.  It uses the same XOR encryption scheme as the EALDR
VM (low byte XOR [[\$03]], high byte XOR [[\$D9]]).

\subsection{attract\_loop (\$0569)}

The entry point for the resident interpreter.  Each iteration swaps
context (zero-page state) and dispatches one bytecode instruction.

<<attract loop>>=
    ORG     $0569
ATTRACT_LOOP:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     CONTEXT_SWAP
    JSR     RESIDENT_DISPATCH
    JMP     ATTRACT_LOOP
@ %def ATTRACT_LOOP

\subsection{context\_swap (\$06E0)}

Swaps 16 bytes between zero page [[\$50]]--[[\$5F]] and [[\$07E5]]--[[\$07F4]].
This gives the resident interpreter its own private set of zero-page
temporaries that don't interfere with the main program.

<<context swap>>=
    ORG     $06E0
CONTEXT_SWAP:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDX     #$0F
.loop:
    LDA     $50,X                   ; load ZP byte
    PHA                             ; save on stack
    LDA     $7E5,X                  ; load shadow byte
    STA     $50,X                   ; → ZP
    PLA                             ; recover old ZP byte
    STA     $7E5,X                  ; → shadow
    DEX
    BPL     .loop
    RTS
@ %def CONTEXT_SWAP

\subsection{resident\_dispatch (\$06B3)}

Dispatches one bytecode instruction using a stack trick.  X and Y hold
the bytecode pointer from the previous iteration.  They are pushed onto
the stack at entry, then [[PULL\_TWO\_RET\_ADDRS]] rearranges the stack
so the saved X/Y values end up in [[\$52/$53]] as the new bytecode pointer.

<<resident dispatch>>=
    ORG     $06B3
RESIDENT_DISPATCH:
    SUBROUTINE

    TXA                             ; \
    PHA                             ;  | save X, Y on stack
    TYA                             ;  | (these ARE the bytecode pointer)
    PHA                             ; /
    JSR     PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS      ; rearrange stack, jump to .resume

    ; Control returns here via JMP ($54):
.resume:
    PLA                             ; \  recover saved Y
    STA     $52                     ;  | $52/$53 = bytecode pointer
    PLA                             ;  | recover saved X
    STA     $53                     ; /

    LDY     #$04                    ; skip 4 bytes
.fetch:
    LDA     ($52),Y                 ; read opcode
    INY
    BNE     .no_carry
    INC     $53
.no_carry:
    TAX                             ; opcode → X (also saves position)
    LDA     RESIDENT_DISPATCH_TABLE,X
    STA     resident_jmp+1          ; self-modify: JMP low byte
resident_jmp:
    JMP     RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH ; self-modified → $07xx
@ %def RESIDENT_DISPATCH
@

[[PULL\_TWO\_RET\_ADDRS]] pulls both return addresses from the stack
(its own and the caller's), increments each by 1 (since RTS pushes
addr\textminus{}1), and jumps through [[\$54/$55]] back to the code
after the [[JSR]] in [[RESIDENT\_DISPATCH]].

<<pull two ret addrs>>=
    ORG     $0738
PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS:
    SUBROUTINE

    PLA                             ; own return addr (low)
    STA     $54
    PLA                             ; own return addr (high)
    STA     $55
    PLA                             ; caller's return addr (low)
    STA     $52
    PLA                             ; caller's return addr (high)
    STA     $53
    INC     $52                     ; +1 (RTS pushed addr-1)
    INC     $54                     ; +1
    BNE     .done
    INC     $55                     ; carry
.done:
    JMP     ($54)                   ; jump back to .resume
@ %def PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS

\subsection{Dispatch table (\$06D3)}

The 18-byte table maps opcode indices to handler addresses in page [[\$07]]:

<<resident dispatch table>>=
    ORG     $06D3
RESIDENT_DISPATCH_TABLE:
    HEX     00 27 55 5F 6D 8A AD B9
    HEX     4F A2 CE 26 79 A2 0F B5
    HEX     50 48
@ %def RESIDENT_DISPATCH_TABLE
@

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccl}
\toprule
\thead{Opcode} & \thead{Table byte} & \thead{Handler address} \\
\midrule
\$00 & \$00 & \$0700 (RESIDENT\_DECODE\_DISPATCH) \\
\$01 & \$27 & \$0727 \\
\$02 & \$55 & \$0755 \\
\$03 & \$5F & \$075F \\
\$04 & \$6D & \$076D \\
\$05 & \$8A & \$078A \\
\$06 & \$AD & \$07AD \\
\$07 & \$B9 & \$07B9 \\
\$08 & \$4F & \$074F \\
\$09 & \$A2 & \$07A2 \\
\$0A & \$CE & \$07CE \\
\$0B & \$26 & \$0726 \\
\$0C & \$79 & \$0779 \\
\$0D & \$A2 & \$07A2 \\
\$0E & \$0F & \$070F \\
\$0F & \$B5 & \$07B5 \\
\$10 & \$50 & \$0750 \\
\$11 & \$48 & \$0748 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Opcodes \$09 and \$0D share the same handler (\$07A2).

\subsection{decode\_encrypted\_addr (\$0710)}

Decodes a 2-byte encrypted address from the bytecode stream.
Uses the same XOR scheme as the EALDR VM.  The decoded address is
left in [[\$54/$55]].

<<decode encrypted addr>>=
    ORG     $0710
DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     ($52),Y                 ; read low byte
    EOR     #$03                    ; decrypt
    INY
    BNE     .no_carry1
    INC     $53
.no_carry1:
    STA     $54                     ; decoded low
    LDA     ($52),Y                 ; read high byte
    INY
    BNE     .no_carry2
    INC     $53
.no_carry2:
    EOR     #$D9                    ; decrypt
    STA     $55                     ; decoded high
    RTS
@ %def DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR

\subsection{resident\_decode\_dispatch (\$0700)}

Opcode \$00 handler---the resident interpreter's GOTO instruction.
Decodes an address and redirects execution there.

<<resident decode dispatch>>=
    ORG     $0700
RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR   ; → $54/$55
    LDA     $54                     ; \
    STA     $52                     ;  | $52/$53 = decoded address
    LDA     $55                     ;  |
    STA     $53                     ; /
    LDY     #$00
    JMP     RESIDENT_DISPATCH.fetch ; fetch from new location
@ %def RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH

\section{Script/event engine (\$795B)}
\label{sec:script_engine}

The script engine runs short bytecode programs that control animations,
sound, and game events.  It is called with a script index in X.

\subsection{Entry and setup}

<<script engine>>=
    ORG     $795B
SCRIPT_ENGINE:
    SUBROUTINE

    STA     $C010                   ; clear keyboard strobe
    LDA     #$00
    STA     ATTRACT_FLAG            ; attract_flag = 0
    CPX     #$06                    ; script index 6 = attract
    BNE     .not_attract
    INC     ATTRACT_FLAG            ; attract_flag = 1
.not_attract:

    CPX     #$02                    ; special setup for index 2
    BEQ     .setup_2
    CPX     #$04                    ; special setup for index 4
    BEQ     .setup_4
    JMP     .load_ptr

.setup_2:
    DEY
    STY     $80D5
    JMP     .load_ptr
.setup_4:
    DEY
    STY     $80E3
@

\subsection{Script pointer table}

The script base address is loaded from the table at [[\$80AE]]:

<<script engine>>=

.load_ptr:
    LDA     SCRIPT_TABLE,X          ; low byte
    STA     $E4
    LDA     SCRIPT_TABLE+1,X        ; high byte
    STA     $E5                     ; $E4/$E5 = script start address
@

<<script pointer table>>=
    ORG     $80AE
SCRIPT_TABLE:
    DC.W    $80C6                   ; script 0
    DC.W    $80C7                   ; script 1
    DC.W    $80D7                   ; script 2
    DC.W    $A300                   ; script 3 (attract -- EALDR resident)
    DC.W    $A3C3                   ; script 4
    DC.W    $A3CE                   ; script 5
    DC.W    $A3DE                   ; script 6
    DC.W    $A409                   ; script 7
@ %def SCRIPT_TABLE
@

Scripts 3--7 are in the [[\$A300]]--[[\$A5FF]] resident region (which was
also copied to [[\$0500]]--[[\$07FF]] by EALDR, but the script table
points to the original addresses).

\subsection{Script interpreter}

<<defines>>=
SCRIPT_LOOP_CTR     EQU     $5A8D   ; script loop iteration counter
SCRIPT_LOOP_ADDR    EQU     $5A8E   ; script loop address (2 bytes)
SCRIPT_GOSUB_ADDR   EQU     $5A90   ; script gosub return address (2 bytes)
SCRIPT_PRNG_MASK    EQU     $5A92   ; PRNG mask for action randomization
SCRIPT_ACTION_VEC   EQU     $5A93   ; action handler vector (2 bytes)
@ %def SCRIPT_LOOP_CTR SCRIPT_LOOP_ADDR SCRIPT_GOSUB_ADDR SCRIPT_PRNG_MASK SCRIPT_ACTION_VEC

After setup, the interpreter initializes its loop counter and PRNG mask:

<<script engine>>=

    LDA     #$00
    STA     SCRIPT_LOOP_CTR         ; loop counter = 0
    LDA     #$01
    STA     SCRIPT_PRNG_MASK        ; PRNG mask = 1
.fetch:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     ($E4),Y                 ; read script byte
    CMP     #$27
    BCC     .control                ; < $27 → control command
    JMP     .action                 ; ≥ $27 → action dispatch
@

\subsubsection{Control commands (< \$27)}

<<script engine>>=

.control:
    CMP     #$25
    BEQ     .cmd_25                 ; set PRNG mask = $0F
    BCS     .cmd_26                 ; $26: PRNG mask = $00

    CMP     #$23
    BEQ     .cmd_23                 ; set action vector → $7A7F
    BCS     .cmd_24                 ; set action vector → $7A91

    CMP     #$21
    BEQ     .cmd_21                 ; gosub
    BCS     .cmd_22                 ; nop (return)

    CMP     #$1F
    BEQ     .cmd_1F                 ; set loop address
    BCS     .cmd_20                 ; set gosub address

    ; --- Loop/end-loop (byte < $1F) ---
    CMP     SCRIPT_LOOP_CTR         ; compare with loop counter
    BEQ     .end_loop
    BCC     .end_loop

    INC     SCRIPT_LOOP_CTR         ; counter++
    LDA     SCRIPT_LOOP_ADDR        ; \
    STA     $E4                     ;  | $E4/$E5 = loop address
    LDA     SCRIPT_LOOP_ADDR+1      ;  |
    STA     $E5                     ; /
    JMP     .fetch

.end_loop:
    LDA     #$00
    STA     SCRIPT_LOOP_CTR         ; reset loop counter
    JMP     SCRIPT_ADVANCE
@

When the byte value equals or exceeds the loop counter, the loop
terminates and the counter resets.  Otherwise, the counter increments
and execution jumps back to the saved loop address.

\subsubsection{Command implementations}

<<script engine>>=

.cmd_25:                            ; PRNG mask = $0F
    LDA     #$0F
    STA     SCRIPT_PRNG_MASK
    JMP     SCRIPT_ADVANCE

.cmd_26:                            ; PRNG mask = $00
    LDA     #$00
    STA     SCRIPT_PRNG_MASK
    JMP     SCRIPT_ADVANCE

.cmd_23:                            ; action vector → $7A7F
    STOW    $7A7F,SCRIPT_ACTION_VEC
    JMP     SCRIPT_ADVANCE

.cmd_24:                            ; action vector → $7A91
    STOW    $7A91,SCRIPT_ACTION_VEC
    JMP     SCRIPT_ADVANCE

.cmd_22:                            ; nop (return from script)
    RTS

.cmd_21:                            ; gosub: jump to saved address
    LDA     SCRIPT_GOSUB_ADDR
    STA     $E4
    LDA     SCRIPT_GOSUB_ADDR+1
    STA     $E5
    JMP     .fetch

.cmd_1F:                            ; set loop address = current+1
    JSR     SCRIPT_INC_E4
    LDA     $E4
    STA     SCRIPT_LOOP_ADDR
    LDA     $E5
    STA     SCRIPT_LOOP_ADDR+1
    JMP     .fetch

.cmd_20:                            ; set gosub address = current+1
    JSR     SCRIPT_INC_E4
    LDA     $E4
    STA     SCRIPT_GOSUB_ADDR
    LDA     $E5
    STA     SCRIPT_GOSUB_ADDR+1
    JMP     .fetch
@

\subsubsection{Action dispatch ($\geq$ \$27)}

When the script byte is [[\$27]] or higher, the PRNG output is masked and
XORed with the action byte, introducing randomness.  The action vector
at [[\$F6]] is set by the handlers at [[SCRIPT\_ACTION\_VEC]].

<<script engine>>=

.action:
    STA     $E2                     ; save action byte
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT             ; PRNG output
    AND     SCRIPT_PRNG_MASK        ; apply mask
    EOR     $E2                     ; XOR with action byte
    STA     $E1                     ; modified action
    JSR     SCRIPT_INC_E4           ; advance script pointer
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     ($E4),Y                 ; read parameter byte
    STA     $E2
    JSR     SCRIPT_ACTION_INDIRECT  ; → JMP (SCRIPT_ACTION_VEC)
    JMP     ($F6)                   ; dispatch via action vector
@ %def SCRIPT_ENGINE

\subsection{advance (\$7A4F)}

The ``advance'' routine is the target of all [[JMP SCRIPT\_ADVANCE]] in
the control commands.  It increments the script pointer, checks for user
input (during attract mode), and loops back to [[.fetch]].

During the attract screen ([[ATTRACT\_FLAG]] = 1), this routine checks for
keyboard or joystick input.  If detected, it returns immediately via RTS,
which exits the entire [[SCRIPT\_ENGINE]] call.

<<script advance>>=
    ORG     $7A4F
SCRIPT_ADVANCE:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     SCRIPT_INC_E4           ; advance script pointer
    LDA     ATTRACT_FLAG            ; attract_flag
    BEQ     .continue               ; not attract mode → skip input check

    ; Attract mode: check keyboard
    LDA     $C000                   ; keyboard register
    BPL     .check_joy              ; no key → check joystick
    RTS                             ; key pressed → exit

.check_joy:
    LDA     $5A00                   ; joystick flag
    BEQ     .continue               ; no joystick → continue script
    LDX     #$00
    LDA     $C061,X                 ; button 0
    BPL     .btn1                   ; not pressed
    RTS                             ; pressed → exit
.btn1:
    INX
    LDA     $C061,X                 ; button 1
    BPL     .continue               ; not pressed → continue
    RTS                             ; pressed → exit

.continue:
    LSR     $5A8C                   ; shift timing flag
    JMP     SCRIPT_ENGINE.fetch     ; loop back to interpreter
@ %def SCRIPT_ADVANCE

\subsection{script helpers}

<<script helpers>>=
    ORG     $7A77
SCRIPT_INC_E4:
    SUBROUTINE

    INC     $E4
    BEQ     .carry
    RTS
.carry:
    INC     $E5
    RTS

    ORG     $7A4C
SCRIPT_ACTION_INDIRECT:
    JMP     (SCRIPT_ACTION_VEC)
@ %def SCRIPT_INC_E4 SCRIPT_ACTION_INDIRECT

\section{Scene data loading (\$6DD8)}

Loads scene-specific data from disk into the [[\$5C00]] region.  The disk
read calls [[\$B300]], which is part of the EALDR disk I/O code still
resident in memory.  If the read fails, the routine fills a byte with
PRNG output (a graceful degradation rather than crashing).

<<load scene data>>=
    ORG     $6DD8
LOAD_SCENE_DATA:
    SUBROUTINE

    BIT     $C0E9                   ; check disk controller
    LDA     #$05                    ; \
    LDY     #$04                    ;  | ($08)+4 = 5 (track configuration)
    STA     ($08),Y                 ; /
    LDA     #$00
    JSR     $6C18                   ; prepare disk parameters
    CLC
    JSR     $B300                   ; EALDR disk read routine
    BCS     .error
    RTS

.error:
    LDY     PRNG_OUTPUT             ; on error: fill with PRNG data
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    STA     $9AA6,Y
    RTS
@ %def LOAD_SCENE_DATA

\section{Unresolved: \$A478}
\label{sec:a478}

The scene loop calls [[JSR \$A478]] every iteration to check for user
input.  This address is in the EALDR region ([[\$A000]]--[[\$BFFF]]),
which remains in memory after the main program starts.

The bytes at [[\$A478]] include the undocumented NMOS 6502 opcode [[\$04]]
(a 2-byte NOP).  This could mean the code legitimately uses undocumented
instructions, or that the region is modified at runtime before being called.

Partial decode:

\begin{verbatim}
    A478: 04 E5         ; NOP $E5 (DOP: 2-byte NOP, reads zp $E5)
    A47A: 19 03 64      ; ORA $6403,Y
    ...
    A483: CA            ; DEX
    A484: D0 FD         ; BNE $A483   (inner delay loop)
    A486: 38            ; SEC
    A487: E9 01         ; SBC #$01
    A489: D0 F6         ; BNE $A481   (outer delay loop)
    A48B: 60            ; RTS
\end{verbatim}

The inner loop at [[\$A483]]--[[\$A484]] ([[DEX; BNE]]) is a standard
delay loop.  The outer loop decrements A and repeats, making this a
nested delay.  The carry flag state on exit likely indicates whether a
key was pressed (C=1) or the timer expired (C=0).  Further analysis
requires an emulator that supports undocumented 6502 opcodes.

\section{Summary}

The attract screen call flow:

\begin{itemize}
  \item [[MAIN\_ENTRY]] ([[\$0800]]): calls [[GAME\_INIT]], then
        [[ATTRACT\_SCREEN]] if [[\$5A01]] is zero.
  \item [[ATTRACT\_SCREEN]] ([[\$09F4]]): sets scene index 1, calls
        [[COMPUTE\_SCENE\_PTR]], tail-calls [[SCENE\_LOOP]] with scene \$26.
  \item [[SCENE\_LOOP]] ([[\$6C37]]): saves ZP pointers, steps PRNG,
        conditionally loads scene data from disk.  In a loop: checks
        keyboard/timer via [[\$A478]], displays status bar, renders scene
        text via [[TEXT\_RENDERER]], runs [[SCRIPT\_ENGINE]] with script \#3.
        Exits when user presses a key or scene sequence ends.
\end{itemize}

Key subsystems:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Text renderer} ([[TEXT\_RENDERER]]): Reads byte streams with
        position commands, pause/reset control codes, and character data
        for the HRCG font.
  \item \textbf{Script engine} ([[SCRIPT\_ENGINE]]): Runs short bytecode
        programs from [[SCRIPT\_TABLE]].  Supports loops, gosub, action
        dispatch with PRNG randomization.
  \item \textbf{Resident interpreter} ([[\$0500]]--[[\$07FF]]): A
        secondary VM copied from EALDR, using context-swapped zero-page
        state and XOR-encrypted addresses.
  \item \textbf{PRNG} ([[STEP\_PRNG]]): Linear congruential generator with
        formula $\texttt{val}_{n+1} = 69 \cdot \texttt{val}_n + \$53
        \pmod{256}$.
\end{itemize}


\chapter{Animating the splash screen}

The [[start_splash_screen]] routine first loads up the initial splash screen,
sets [[indirect_routine]] to [[note_played]], and begins the sound routine by
calling [[start_sound]].

[[note_played]] plots a mob, then sets [[indirect_routine]] to [[splash_routine_2]]
and jumps to [[next_table_entry]].

[[splash_routine_2]] calls a routine first with [[$5E1F]] then with [[$5E3A]],
then jumps to [[splash_screen_step]].

[[splash_screen_step]] then sets [[indirect_routine]] to [[splash_routine_1]]
then [[splash_routine_0]] and calls [[set_splash_routine]] within [[note_played]].
After that, [[splash_screen_step]] presumably moves mobs around.


When the user ends the splash screen, the [[start_splash_screen]] routine
replaces the indirect jump to [[indirect_routine]] in [[start_sound]] to an
absolute jump to [[next_table_entry]], since there is no further need to
animate while playing sound.


